{{Distinguish|Sa'ad ad-Din II}} {{Infobox islands | name = Sa'ad ad-Din Islands | image name = | image caption = | locator map = | map caption = | nickname = | location = [[Somalia]] | coordinates = From {{Coord|11|29.5|N|43|17|E}} to {{Coord|11|21|N|43|28|E}} | archipelago = [[Zeila]] Archipelago | total islands = 6 | major islands = Sa'ad ad-Din, Aibat | area_km2 = | length_km = | width_km = | highest mount = | elevation_m = | population = | population as of = | density_km2 = | ethnic groups = [[Somali people|Somalis]] ([[Ciise]] sub-clan) | country = {{flag|Somalia}} | additional info = }}
The '''Sa'ad ad-Din Islands''' ({{lang-so|''Sacadin jasiiradaha''}}, {{lang-ar|سعد الدين إد جزر}}), also [[Sa'ad ad-Din Islands#Etymology|Romanized]] as '''Sa'ad-ed-din'''{{sfn|H.N. Moldenke and A.L. Moldenke|1980|p=502}} and known as the '''Zeila Archipelago''',{{sfn|Jason Gurney|1966|p=74}} are group of [[island]]s off the northern coast of [[Somalia]]. They are situated near the ancient city of [[Zeila]].{{sfn|T. R. McClanahan|2000|p= 273}}
==Etymology== The name for the [[archipelago]] comes from the [[Somali people|Somali]] [[Sultan]] [[Sa'ad ad-Din II]] who was killed by Emperor [[Yeshaq I]] of [[Ethiopian Empire|Abyssinia]] on the main island in 1415.{{sfn|Philip Briggs|2012|p=10}}{{sfn|Mohamed Diriye Abdullahi|2001|p=16}} Along with his name, there many different spelling for the island such as ''Sa'ad ed Din'',{{sfn|T. R. McClanahan|2000|p= 273}} ''Sa'ad-ed-din'',{{sfn|H.N. Moldenke and A.L. Moldenke|1980|p=502}} and ''Sa'ad-ad-Din''.{{sfn|Frederick Mercer Hunter|1877|p=11}} The archpeliogo is also known as the ''Zeila Archipelago''{{sfn|Jason Gurney|1966|p=74}} and the ''Sa'ad ad-Din group''.<ref name="chdjc"/>
==Overview== The Sa'ad ad-Din archipelago is made of six small island all of which are low-lying and have sandy [[beaches]].<ref name="chdjc">{{cite web|url=http://www.reefbase.org/global_database/dbr1,12,SOM,270.aspx |title=ReefBase:: Global Database: Resources - Overview - Eastern Africa - Somalia |accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref><ref name="yfo6ul">{{cite web|url=http://www.persga.org/Files/Common/Sea_Birds/Reginal_Status_of_Seabirds.pdf |title=Regional Status of Breeding Seabirds in the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref> The largest of these islands are ''Sa'ad ad-Din'' and ''Aibat'',<ref name="xtuhus">{{cite web|url=http://www.persga.org/Files/Common/MPA/4_Survey_Design_final_fINAL_1.pdf |title=Survey design for Proposed Marine Protected Areas |page=29 |accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref> which are six and nine miles off the coast of [[Zeila]], respectively.{{sfn|National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|2007|p=176}} There is also a [[lighthouse]] at Aibat.{{sfn|National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|2007|p=176}}
==Environment== The Sa'ad ad-Din Islands are well known for their splendid [[coral reefs]] similar to those found on the southern coast of [[Oman]].{{sfn|T. R. McClanahan|2000|p= 273}} These reefs are the most diverse and well formed coral reefs on the coast of the [[Gulf of Aden]]<ref name="gkftu">{{cite web|url=http://eeas.europa.eu/delegations/somalia/documents/more_info/country_environmental_profile_somalia_en.pdf |title=Country Environmental Profile for Somalia |page=8 |date= |accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref> and possibly the largest in the region.<ref name="werff">{{cite web|url=http://www.persga.org/Files//Common/MPA/MPA_Network_DetailedReport_2003.pdf |title=Development and management of a network of marine protected areas in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden region |page= 745|date= |accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref> From provincial counts, ninety-nine different species of [[coral]] from forty-three different [[genera]]s have been found on the islands.{{sfn|T. R. McClanahan|2000|p= 273}}
There are also a hundred and thirty-two different species of [[Coral reef fish|coral fish]] found around the archipelago. Many of these species include those also found in the [[Red Sea]], Gulf of Aden, and the [[Indian Ocean]].{{sfn|T. R. McClanahan|2000|p= 274}}
The island of Sa'ad ad-Din and Aibat (called ''Ceebaad'' in [[Somali language|Somali]]){{sfn|National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|2007|p=175}} both are sites of major bird colonies.{{sfn|Nigel Redman|2009|p= 29}} On the island of Sa'ad ad-Din alone, there were more than 100,000 breeding pairs recorded.<ref name="xtuhus">{{cite web|url=http://www.persga.org/Files/Common/MPA/4_Survey_Design_final_fINAL_1.pdf |title=Survey design for Proposed Marine Protected Areas |page=20 |accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref>
Following the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]], the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) and other [[NGO]] worked with local authorizes to establish protected areas and monitor fishers on the islands.{{sfn|United Nations Environment Programme.|2005|p=132}}
==Demographics== The inhabitants of the archipelago are [[Somali people|Somalis]] from the [[Gadabuursi]] sub-clan, a sub-division of the larger [[Dir (clan)|Dir clan]].{{sfn|Élisée Reclus|1866|p= 204}} The locals have established [[Coral reef fish|reef fishing]] communities on the islands.{{sfn|T. R. McClanahan|2000|p= 274}}{{sfn|M. H. Schleyer, Robert M. Baldwin|1999|p=10}}
