{{unreferenced|date=March 2016}} {{Location map |Indian Ocean |label=Northern Coral Group |lon_dir=E |lat_dir=S |lat_deg=6|lat_min=30 |lon_deg=55|lon_min=44 |position=right |width=250 |float=right |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg |marksize=20 |caption=Location of the Northern Coral Group in the Indian Ocean }}
'''Northern Coral Group''' is a collective term for two islands of [[Geography of Seychelles#Inner Islands|Inner Islands]] of the [[Seychelles]], lying in the north of the island nation, between 92 and 102 kilometers north of the capital, [[Victoria, Seychelles|Victoria]], on [[Mahé, Seychelles|Mahé]] Island.
==Islands== Two widely separated islands, with a distance of 53&nbsp;km from one another, make up the Northern Coral Group. They are both sand cays, situated on the northeastern sides of pseudo-[[atoll]]s: #[[Bird Island, Seychelles|Bird]] in the west #[[Denis Island|Denis]] in the east
==Population== Both islands are inhabited. The main settlement is [[Denis Island|St. Denis]].
